-- Renault Said to Seek $1 Billion from Public Sale of German Auto Loan Bonds
-- Esteban Duarte
-- 2010-06-23T16:02:38Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-23/renault-said-to-seek-1-billion-from-public-sale-of-german-auto-loan-bonds.html

          
          
             Renault SA,  France’s second-biggest
carmaker, plans to raise 873 million euros ($1 billion) from its
first public sale of bonds backed by German auto loans.  
 The securities, bundling 251,270 loans provided by RCI
Banque Germany, will have an average life of 1.78 years and are
expected to receive top AAA ratings, according to a presentation
sent to investors.  
 Renault plans to meet European investors next week and set
final prices on the notes by July 5, according to the
presentation. The company, based in Boulogne Billancourt,
France, hasn’t sold asset-backed bonds in the public market in
Europe since 2007 when it issued 874 million euros of bonds
securitizing Italian loans.  
 The notes will be issued through Cars Alliance Auto Loans
Germany 2010-1. Credit Agricole SA and Societe Generale SA are
managing the sale, according to the presentation.  
